04026nam a22006735i 9780271034799DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20072007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710347997 a10.1515/97802710347992doi  a(DE-B1597)583650  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHD6145b.H26 2007eb 7aSOC0100002bisacsh04a331.40944/090332221 aHafter, Daryl M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen at Work in Preindustrial France /cDaryl M. Hafter. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b12 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Political Economy of Guilds -- t2. The Uses of Gender in Economic Life -- t3. Guildwomen and Ouvrières -- t4. Turgot's Reforms and Their Aftermath -- t5. Paths to the Revolution -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe subject of women as skilled workers in the eighteenth century is central to our understanding of the history of work and technology in the preindustrial age. While recent scholarship has dispelled the notion that women did not enter the workforce until the Industrial Revolution, debate continues as to the extent to which women actually participated in skilled work in the preceding decades. This book draws upon substantial archival research in Rouen, Lyon, and Paris to show that while the vast majority of working women in eighteenth-century France labored at unskilled, low-paying jobs, it was not at all unusual for women to be actively engaged in economic activities as workers, managers, and merchants. Some even developed vertically integrated wholesale and retail businesses, while others became indispensable to manufacturers through their technical skill. In fact, Hafter documents how certain women guild masters were able to exploit the legal system to achieve considerable economic independence, power, wealth, and legal parity with male masters. She also shows how gender politics complicated the day-to-day experience of these working women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDiscrimination in employmentzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aSex discrimination against womenzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aWomen in guildszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenxEmploymentzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aWorking class womenzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271034799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271034799.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK